definitions: not suitable or safe for eating due to being poisonous, spoiled, or too unpleasant
examples: The mushrooms looked appealing but were completely inedible
She threw away the inedible parts of the fish

definitions: too great, extreme, or beautiful to be expressed or described adequately in words
examples: She felt an ineffable joy when she held her newborn
The sunset created an ineffable sense of peace

definitions: not producing the desired effect or unable to achieve the intended purpose
examples: The new policy proved ineffective at reducing traffic
His ineffective leadership caused the project to fail

definitions: not producing the desired effect and lacking the ability or confidence to succeed
examples: The manager made ineffectual attempts to control the situation
His ineffectual protests were ignored by everyone

definitions: not achieving maximum productivity with minimum wasted effort, expense, or time
examples: The old heating system was inefficient and costly
Their inefficient work methods slowed down production

definitions: not having the right to do or obtain something through not satisfying the appropriate conditions
examples: He was ineligible for the scholarship due to low grades
Non-citizens are ineligible to vote in national elections

definitions: having or showing no skill or ability to do something correctly or well
examples: The inept waiter spilled soup on several customers
Her inept handling of the crisis made things worse

definitions: unfair or unjust in the way people or groups are treated differently
examples: The inequitable distribution of resources caused social tension
They challenged the inequitable hiring practices in court

definitions: lacking the ability or strength to move or act physically
lacking vigor or having no chemical or biological action on other substances
examples: The patient lay inert on the hospital bed
The drug remained inert until mixed with water
Helium is an inert gas that doesn't react
The inert ingredients serve only as fillers

definitions: unable to be avoided, ignored, or denied because of being so obvious or prevalent
examples: Death is an inescapable part of human existence
The inescapable conclusion was that he had lied

definitions: having such abundance that it will never be used up or come to an end
examples: She seemed to have an inexhaustible supply of energy
The desert's inexhaustible heat made travel difficult

definitions: impossible to stop or prevent from continuing in a relentless, unalterable way
examples: The inexorable march of time affects us all
Economic forces led to inexorable changes in society

definitions: not costing a lot of money and therefore affordable for most people
examples: They found an inexpensive hotel near the beach
The restaurant serves good, inexpensive meals to students

definitions: having little knowledge or skill in a particular area due to lack of practical experience
examples: The inexperienced driver struggled with parallel parking
They hired inexperienced workers and trained them

definitions: unable to be explained or understood because no reason or cause can be found
examples: His inexplicable behavior worried his family
There was an inexplicable noise coming from the attic

definitions: incapable of making mistakes or being wrong in any judgment or action
examples: No human being is infallible in their decisions
She had an infallible memory for people's names

definitions: well known for some bad quality, deed, or negative characteristic throughout history
examples: The prison housed many infamous criminals
This street is infamous for its dangerous traffic

definitions: displaying behavior that is childish, immature, or characteristic of an infant
examples: His infantile tantrums embarrassed everyone at dinner
She criticized their infantile approach to problem-solving

definitions: possessed by an intense but short-lived passion or attraction for someone or something
examples: He became infatuated with his new coworker
She was infatuated with the idea of fame

definitions: not possible to do easily or conveniently due to practical difficulties or constraints
examples: The proposed budget cuts were politically infeasible
Building a bridge there would be financially infeasible

definitions: affected by disease-causing organisms such as bacteria, viruses, or parasites
examples: The infected wound required immediate medical attention
Several computers were infected with malicious software

definitions: liable to be transmitted to people through the environment or direct contact
spreading quickly from one person to another through emotional influence or enthusiasm
examples: The patient has an infectious disease requiring isolation
Measles is highly infectious among unvaccinated children
Her infectious laughter filled the entire room
His infectious enthusiasm motivated the whole team

definitions: able to cause infection by transmitting disease-causing organisms to a host
examples: The infective agent spread rapidly through the population
This strain is highly infective in laboratory conditions

definitions: derived from reasoning and drawing conclusions rather than from explicit statements or direct observation
examples: The study relied on inferential statistics for analysis
Her inferential reasoning skills helped solve the mystery

definitions: lower in quality, value, or importance compared to something else
lower in rank, status, or position within a hierarchy or structure
examples: The knockoff products were clearly inferior quality
This wine is inferior to what we had yesterday
Junior staff occupied inferior positions in the company
The inferior court's decision was later overturned

definitions: of, relating to, or characteristic of hell or the underworld
extremely annoying, troublesome, or unpleasant in an informal sense
examples: The painting depicted infernal scenes of punishment
Dante wrote about the infernal regions
That infernal noise kept me awake all night
She couldn't fix the infernal machine

definitions: unable to produce offspring or fruit, or unable to support plant growth
examples: The couple sought treatment for infertile conditions
The infertile soil couldn't support any crops

definitions: limitless or endless in space, extent, or size, impossible to measure or calculate
examples: The universe may contain infinite stars and planets
She showed infinite patience with difficult students

definitions: so small as to be almost nothing, immeasurably or incalculably minute
examples: The chances of winning were infinitesimal
Scientists measured infinitesimal changes in temperature

definitions: not physically or mentally strong, especially through age or illness
examples: The infirm residents needed constant care and attention
His infirm grandfather could barely walk unassisted

definitions: red, swollen, and painful as a result of infection or injury
provoked to strong feelings of anger, passion, or other intense emotion
examples: The inflamed tissue needed treatment with antibiotics
His inflamed joints made movement painful
The politician's speech inflamed public opinion
Their inflamed rhetoric worsened the conflict

definitions: relating to or causing redness, swelling, and pain in body tissue
tending to arouse anger, hostility, or strong emotional reactions
examples: The patient took medicine for inflammatory conditions
Arthritis is an inflammatory disease of joints
His inflammatory comments sparked heated debate
The newspaper published inflammatory articles about immigration

definitions: capable of being filled with air or gas to increase in size
examples: The children played with inflatable beach balls
They used an inflatable mattress for camping

definitions: distended with air or gas to appear larger than normal
exaggerated or increased beyond what is reasonable, accurate, or justified
examples: The fully inflated balloon floated to the ceiling
Check that your tires aren't over inflated
His inflated ego made him difficult to work with
The company reported inflated profits to investors

definitions: relating to or tending to cause a general increase in prices and fall in purchasing value
examples: The government tried to control inflationary pressures
Printing more money often has inflationary effects

definitions: unwilling to change or compromise, or unable to be changed or adapted
not capable of being bent or flexed physically without breaking
examples: His inflexible attitude created problems at work
The inflexible rules allowed no exceptions
The inflexible metal rod couldn't be shaped
Her spine had become inflexible with age

definitions: having a relaxed, friendly, or unofficial style, manner, or nature
examples: The meeting had an informal atmosphere
She prefers informal clothing for weekend activities

definitions: serving to provide facts, data, or knowledge rather than entertainment or persuasion
examples: The website includes informational videos about health
They distributed informational brochures to visitors

definitions: providing useful, helpful, or interesting information that increases knowledge or understanding
examples: The documentary was both entertaining and informative
She gave an informative presentation about climate change

definitions: having or showing knowledge of a particular subject or situation based on study or experience
examples: Voters should make informed decisions at elections
His informed opinion carried weight in discussions

definitions: relating to electromagnetic radiation with wavelengths longer than visible light but shorter than radio waves
examples: The security camera uses infrared technology
Infrared heaters warm objects rather than air

definitions: not occurring often or not happening at regular or short intervals
examples: His visits home became increasingly infrequent
The bus service is infrequent on weekends

definitions: made extremely angry and impatient to the point of losing self-control
examples: She was infuriated by their lack of respect
The infuriated customer demanded to see the manager

definitions: causing extreme anger or impatience by being very annoying or frustrating
examples: The infuriating delay caused us to miss our flight
His infuriating habit of interrupting annoyed everyone

definitions: showing remarkable cleverness, originality, and inventiveness in solving problems or creating things
examples: She devised an ingenious solution to save water
The ingenious design won several engineering awards

definitions: firmly fixed or established as a habit, belief, or attitude difficult to change
examples: Years of training had ingrained good study habits
Their ingrained prejudices were hard to overcome

definitions: occupied or lived in by people or animals as a dwelling place
examples: The island has been inhabited for thousands of years
Only three inhabited houses remained in the village

definitions: existing in something as a permanent, essential, or characteristic attribute that cannot be separated
examples: There are inherent risks in mountain climbing
She believed in the inherent goodness of people

definitions: received as a genetic trait from parents or received as property or position from predecessors
examples: His inherited wealth came from his grandmother
The inherited disease affected multiple family members

definitions: in the process of receiving property, traits, or characteristics from parents or predecessors
examples: The inheriting relatives gathered for the will reading
Children inheriting these genes may develop similar conditions
